comment:
I will stake my own life on this statement...

That lady Amber is a bonafide narcissistic sociopath, through & through. Everything I've seen and heard about her, which I've now sat and watched hours of today , I've seen a mirror likeness of before. She is cold, calculating, methodical! Bitterness & resentment governs her every action and emotion. 

Johnny Depp was/IS in the fight of his life to escape her clutches, and I FULLY BELIEVE one of the comments he made, when he said, "He was scared to death and didn't know what to do." He said it because he realized he fell in love with pure evil and the only escape he had would be a never ending nightmare, which he's been living now for years!! He knew it, and I assure you, he foresaw the outcome he now fights with. 

We have not heard the last of Amber Heard. If we could ever a fly on the wall, or secretly record what her own sister has to say about her, THAT is where we'd find the real truth. Her family knows what she is and what she's capable of, but say nothing b/c they are trapped in her web too! I again stake my life on that fact!

Here is the absolute truth about what happens when your sociopath partner knows you've figured them out... YOU BECOME THEIR PUREST ENEMY & NOTHING IS HELD BACK FOR THEM TO DESTROY EVERYTHING THEY CAN ABOUT YOU! And I mean everything.

comment: honestly just shows the double standards of our society. Equal means BOTH sides get the same opportunities and rights. Clearly society is not equal as Amber never actually managed to conclusively prove that Johnny beat her yet in the eyes of society, he was a wife beater. This is because society seems to assume that if a woman comes froward with an allegation of anything against a man, he is guilty and she is the victim. I'm not denying that many women are abused by men, I am just saying that women do have a massive advantage when it comes to accusing men of things in court and even if what they are saying is completely false, the man could lose countless things he holds dear such as his job, his family, and his reputation. Even when it has been proven that Amber Heard had beaten Johnny, society still treats him like the abuser. The only marginally good thing I can take from this is if when all those film companies come running back to Depp to give him his roles he refuses and screws every single one of them over. I am a huge fan of the Pirates of the Caribbean franchise but I swear it would be 10x better to watch them squabble over what to do without Jack Sparrow than seeing a new movie come out that'll make them much richer. I also want to say that this issue shouldn't become a men vs women issue like every gender issue does; the issue is simply that we thing the CJS works on an innocent until proven guilty platform. Well, until we truly use that idea and stop making exceptions, we might just find ourselves some equality. Massive respect to the people who stayed neutral throughout all of this, you are the people society needs to learn from.

I 100% believe that she abused him. However, Johnny Depp has been an alcoholic for years, and it's only gotten worse. He was arrested several times, once for smashing up a hotel room during a fight with his girlfriend at the time. Throwing and smashing things in order to intimidate others, is one of the most common signs of physical abuse to come, or that is currently happening. Again, she's an abuser and needs to pay for it. BUT, I believe that he has violent tendencies, based on his past. Many abusers don't choose to abuse some of their partners, but do end up abusing one or more. comment: This case shines light on a larger issue of today that men growing up in this world must face. It is true that throughout past centuries the has been a patriarchy, a world where men have ruled, but that time is no more. However, some now believe it is right to treat men in an unfair way in cases such as these, adopting a policy "guilty until proven innocent", where in many places around the world the justice system prides itself on being the opposite. In a modern day setting, a man can be accused of rape allegations, whether true or false, but no matter the case, that will stay with them for the rest of their lives, but the woman will leave unscathed (if false). A woman can make a claim that a man is domestically abusing her, and that word is taken as bible by some, and can (and has) stopped men from being able to forward in careers. However, all of this leads to a massive double standard, if a man claims of domestic abuse, he can be told to "man up", or can even be laughed at by authorities. A man can say he has been raped by a woman, well, sexually abused because technically a man can't be raped by a woman, anyways, and again, he will be laughed at, made a mockery. Another issue with rape charges is that in some countries, a woman can give explicit consent during the act without being under any influence, and then the next morning decide she didn't want it, and that is then a rape case. If you think I am saying all this without any evidence to back it up, you'd be mistaken. My cousin went to a bar one evening with some friends, he was 19 at the time, and these you women walked up claiming to be 18, and coming on very strongly to them all. My cousin ended up prpcreating with one of them, to later find out she was actually 16, which in my country is illegal. As a result of this, he was accused of rape, and although the jury decided he was not guilty due to lack of knowledge, the best job he can now get is in construction, after being thrown out of his University course. Many people will say to this that it is us men whining about things just because they affect us, and that they are minor things in the grand scheme of the world, and not a problem, but movements like the "#metoo" movement have encouraged this behaviour. A  woman can accuse a man of rape purely out of dislike for him, and whether true or false, that will ruin the mans life, and as we have seen in this case, with evidence against Amber's claims, she still has all of her roles, no-one is refusing to offer her roles, and Depp with his large resume and amazing career, now has to give that career up, or it definitely looked like that for a long amount of time, and yes, he has the money to still lie, more than enough in fact, but that's not the point. He has to give up something he loves to do due to alleged crimes that have not been proven at all. Many parents today are worried to raise a male child due to this. A parent has to say to his/her child that they need to be careful and that they could be ruined for no reason just from an allegation. A parents job is to warn and protect your child, but how are you able to protect a child from that? Sure, say don't rape someone, but that's common sense, you cannot protect your child from this world. In todays world, if you are a white male you are told that by being born you have been privileged, that you are advantaged, that you are what's wrong with this world. Correct me if I'm wrong, but the argument against sexism and racism is that we cannot control how we are born, so why is that instantly different for a different cause? Modern feminism says that men are awful people, that we are less than women, that we, by being male, are instantly a rapist, a misogynist, that instantly you are wrong. I do not disagree that sexism and racism still exist, but it is far less than it used to be. If you look internationally, sexism rates are scarily high, yes. Do you know why? In some middle eastern countries it is in the law that women are less than men, that women can't drive, women can't do this, can't do that, that is why sexism is alarmingly high. In modern settings, racism and sexism are barely issues. If you look at the issues of the BLM movement, police statistics published before the riots claimed that 4 in every 100,000 black people in custody were killed, where as 5 in every 100,000 white people in custody were killed (it may have been in 10,000, I am unsure), but the point is that the whole police force isn't racist. Now, stop and searches are a different story, but in my own personal experience, if I had to choose walking by a group of white teenagers, or a group of black teenagers, I would choose the whit teenagers. Yes, call me racist, but that's how I personally have been raised. It so happened that when I was growing up, much more crime in my area was being committed by black teenagers than white, and so I have less trust for black people when I don't know them. However, one of my best friends is black. And he actually agrees with me that black people tend to be less trustworthy in terms of strangers. It is also a fact that the majority of protestors at the BLM riots were actually white people, not black, Why? Because white people feel as if they should atone for how they were born, they feel that racism is institutionalised, that it is almost taught like German children under Nazi rule were taught that Jews were evil. All I'm saying is that we need to focus on bigger issues, ones like Climate change. Yes, it's nice to have a cause to fight for, but make sure it's the right one. We could argue all day and all night about whether racism or sexism is a major issue or not, but at the end of the day, it won't matter when we are all cooked up like some flipping potato chips!!! Just make sure we are trying to make the right change in the world, once a future is secure, then we can discuss the fairness of it. The average lifespan of a mammal species is tens of millions. We have only been here for hundreds of thousands. Our legacy as a species will be smart, but not smart enough. We will be the smartest species to roam the Earth, and the quickest to kill it unless we sort ourselves out. Instead of rioting against things and dedicating your life to these causes, instead, be the change that you want to see (yes, Markiplier), instead of fighting it, focus on yourself. Don't be racist or sexist, and make sure to set that example to your (future) children. Do that, and in a couple of generations, these issues will be forgotten about. Yes it's a long time, but people are not going to change their ways. The old generation still makes racist/sexist remarks, but they have learnt to keep it to themselves, or within family who will understand. If these people who have formed habits over decades can change to the time, before being told to do so, then so can you. I hope you enjoyed my rant! i can see a potential for backlash, hence why it's so long............ hopefully people won't read it, lol.

comment:
I might not be a divorce counselor or someone who deals with abusers daily, but I've been abused mentally and physically before and I do read some psychology for fun, and the most common form of manipulation that an abuser uses is "downplay." By berating and undermining the victims allegations as childish as Amber herd does or dismissing the claims as being petty is what allows abuser to constantly get away with abuse, because the most confident answer/person is most of the time the one which is believed. Her comment on the tape that Depps claims are childish makes her look crystal clear that she is the perpetrator. In no logical sense would a person who is being abused, belittle the abuser because, why would you try and diminish the person as being childish if he really was an abuser, if the abuser is childish and petty, that doesn't fit the narrative of the abuser being the dominant person in a relationship which is the 9/10 times. Notice how she constantly want control as well, another thing which is always a trait on manipulative and abusive people, she wants control by interrupting Depp and being the first to show anger. 110% Amber herd is the perpetrator 
I rest my case.

comment:
It is good that this happened. I pity Depp but this entire thing was an example that needed to be made. It was good that half the planet sided with Amber Heard right from the start for no reason other than, she's the woman.
It was good that all of these fools were shown the extent of their stupidity. This entire situation is a perfect example of the blind spots our society at large has and the ignorances that many of us have had and still have to this day. 

I was raised in a household where ''equality'' was the word of the day but equality literally just meant inequality. It was literally an overcompensation resulting in anything but equality.
My sister was straight up given more than me, treated better than me to bring about 'equality'. What is equal about giving your son 50 dollars pocket money and your daughter 100 dollars over the course of their entire childhood? 
is 50=100? 
I may have failed math due to the lack of comfort in my family home at the time but seriously... what the actual fuck does the word equality mean? Does it have anything to do with the mathematical symbol called equals??!?!?!?!? 50 is not =100 no matter how hard we pretend that it is. 


Person A gets 50
Person B gets 100
And this is done under the guise of equality.

FYI, my sister is a biologist now and I work at a carpenter because the stress at home led to me throwing my education away.
Equality... 
What does it mean?

comment: I was married to a sociopath.  Sociopaths love to control their partner.  You don't fall in love with the sociopath, because they don't let you see that part of themselves.   After a year or so, you've seen glimpses, and you know that something is wrong. Over the years ,they chip away at you, over and over, beating you down, blaming you for everything, verbally abusing you, gaslighting-- in ten years of marriage, my husband apologized to me once.  It was a nightmare, and even after he'd left, he would call and talk as if we were getting back together.  It's just all part of the sick game of manipulation.  Those of us who lived through a relationship with a sociopath, you recognize it.  I had ignored the story about Depp's personal life, to give him privacy.  I don't like gossip, but I couldn't believe Johnny Depp would ever hurt anyone.  It seems like every time he didn't come when she called, when he refused to stay in the room when she wanted a fist fight, that he was willing to leave the marriage and not let her pull the strings to control him, she lashed out to hurt him publicly.  She has loved every second of it.  She'll get what she deserves

comment: Makes me sick. Being a child of abuse, every female that was suppose to take care of me as a child wind up taking their anger out on me because they never spoke up to those they had imaginary grievances towards. My babysitter  wouldn't allow me to use the bathroom, force to piss myself she then made me wear girls panties in front of the other kids. Eventually this led to having a UTI. Had a narcissistic mother who would brag to friends what objects she could brake on me and not leave a mark on my face. Eventually social services did visit but I played along that everything was fine, all the while wishing otherwise. This accumulated with my grandmothers favorite way of beating me with a tennis racket. I remember seeing school messages about abuse and sexual abuse but it was always geared towards women. Us "Men" were taught socially to man up. The only people who treated me with respect was my grandfather and step-dad, of course they were just evil men to the matriarchs of the household. Eventually this led to years of addiction, OCD, suicidal thoughts and self blaming. Everything turned around when I had a daughter of my own. Promised myself I'd never put her through what I went through. Luckily, I found a passion through art and am now sober. But everyday I still struggle with depression and PTSD. I firmly believe we need more emotional standings for male and females. This cancel culture is truly a shortcut to real critical thinking that just helps to turn a blind eye. Not really sure why I decided now to write this but I hope it keeps the discussion going beyond just headline fodder.

comment:
As a person who survived domestic abuse, I feel physically ill when I see her. It's just as much mental as physical. Abusers make you question your self, your reality and the validity of your thoughts and feelings... Did I really make this happen? Do I actually deserve this? I'm not worthy of more, am I? 

They set out to destroy you so that they can feel bigger. And, as time goes on, it takes more and more to make them feel bigger so they have to do more abusive things. 

But you can't tear someone else down to build yourself up; it just doesn't work. So, in the end, they must do their best to destroy either their victim or themselves. Guess which option they usually pick?

How dare she try to destroy such a pure soul? I hope she rots in hell.

comment:
I don't know why but every time I hear or read about this situation I get really emotional, most of the time I cry a bit. 

From what I have seen, Johnny is a kind soul. No one deserves the treatment he got from Amber and subsequently other people. And that clip where the woman asked what happened to his finger just killed me, as did the audio where he was trying to say she punched him in the face. 

Some people have told me it's ridiculous to care so much about what's going on with this since I don't personally know him or because so many people have it worse. To that I say how would you feel if that was your friend, cousin, or brother? What if it was your son? I could be wrong about this bc I read it so long ago, but I think he contracted (is that the word?) MRSA 3 times from the injury on his finger, which is insane! I hope everything turns out in his favor and that he can get his name cleared, and I hope Amber gets exactly what she deserves.

comment: Johny is a great actor and to be honest, I like all his films.  Amber is ruining his career for what? because she told a lie and now can't undo the damage she has done? is it a question of money or honor?  I am pretty sure if everyone in the USA wasn't ready to sue at the drop of a dime, she could apologize and in a few years, all of this would be forgotten.  Everyone lies, big ones,  little ones, whether it's to protect someone's feelings or to protect yourself.  I try to live my life lie free and say the truth all the time but even I sometimes realize that not everyone is ready to accept or hear the truth. Would I tell a 5-year-old child, who worked all day on something they made for me ugly, or say it was the best gift they had ever given me?  It's never too late, to tell the truth, and apologize.  So Amber needs to put on her big girl pants and say I screwed up and face the consequences of those actions.  I would have far more respect for her if she did that than continue, this bullshit story and let things continue to spiral out of control.  It's a big problem in our society we deal in absolute and have difficulty accepting that people aren't infallible.  We need to leave room for forgiveness and accountability.

comment:
According to HER parents, this was all because she didn't want to leave the apartment they had and they said according to her lawyer, she had to claim abuse in order to stay in that apartment.  Otherwise he had grounds to have her removed (I believe he owned it before they got together). Her parents apparently still speak with him and side with him. They have copies of text messages between her parents and Johnny stating the things about the lawyer telling her she must claim abuse. That they are fine with him and they still care about him. Basically letting him know that his issues with their daughter do not impact the fact that they care for him. Funny thing, I believe he actually told her she could stay in the apartment as long as she needed, but she wanted to OWN it  and have his name removed. Pure greed. I honestly believe based on things I have heard about him, that he would have given her the apartment. 

I often stand with the women that say they are abused, but in this case she just seems to be lying. She abused another partner and I believe she was arrested for it. I believe HE was abused. 

She needs removed from all these movies. He needs his contracts back. He is the victim in all of this I believe.  

They did not have children together, correct? He has 2 children with his ex-girlfriend only, right? I don't see her as a person that would put her children first. I've never heard her mention her step kids even ONCE. Never expressed concern as to how this may be effecting them...

I love his instant response of making sure the kids are ok and not to hate each other just because you were no longer together. 

I know some people seem to think he's acting, and he's a very good actor, but I believe him about how he knows the kids come first, not actively trying to hate your ex, and being a good person in general. I don't think Amber is a good actor and she's definitely NOT pulling this off when you watch her.

In my experience women are more hateful and vicious  abusers.   Looking at AH's eyes when she was telling her version of what happened I saw that same glare inheritance eyes I witnessed 50 years ago.   I met JD once when he was filming a movie near me.   A group of us (his fans) stood waiting.   He approached us and talked with us,  allowed pictures and was a very gracious man to us.   There was no rudeness,  not disrespect or anger towards us even though I am very sure he was eager to go to where he was staying after a day of filming.   I do not believe a man with such kindness towards children,  his family,  friends and fans would be capable of committing any act such as those he was accused of unless he was protecting himself against being abused. While on the other hand AH has been arrested for dv committed against a previous partner.   She has admitted to throwing pots and pans at JD along with hitting,  punching or slapping him on tape,  whichever you prefer to call it it is still the same.
